snippet.textDisplay:
Disclaimer: I talk about the craziness so if you wish an opportunity to think about it less than is possible today, I recommend stopping now.

Is YouTube itself encouraging shying away from naming *the craziness*? I remember seeing something to that effect, possibly something to do with curbing misinformation, but I could very well be wrong. It seems like a poor choice to me, allowing more gravitas to gather around the name than would normally. I think it should be given the power and the respect proportionate to its importance, yes, but no more. Let's not make it any spookier than a microscopic, nigh-invisible enemy with the capacity to kill our loved ones already is.

At the end of the day, though, I'm just some guy spouting opinions onto the internet under a quite unrelated video. Have a good day, dear reader, and I apologize if I've added any stress to it.

snippet.textDisplay: I don’t think it’s about staying in the middle of the road politically. snippet.textDisplay:
I love CinemaWins and CinemaSins, but just hear me out. It might just be because I’m as sleep deprived as I’ll ever be, but what if they [CinemaWins/Sins crew] analyzed everything great and wrong with music videos or songs? I know M/V’s are short, but, heck, they could do entire albums at a time or go really in depth on anything to be said. I know, I’m crazy, but it would be really interesting to see them going into their thoughts on overall tone of a song, cool sets in M/V’s, choreography and translations (when they apply), and maybe even stating their belief of what the lyrics or symbolisms in the videos mean. Heck, I already know that at least some of the crew are really in love with music [see how much they talk about scores] and facial expression.
(please don’t bash on me, I know I’m insane)

Just watched this film last night. I enjoyed it except for 2 things;
1) Craig's voice was unnecessary and annoying. I don't know why some directors want to do this. It's like Sam Jackson in Kingsman.
2) I'm not a CSI, but Harlan killed himself probably 20 feet away from Marta. I don't believe blood flies that far. Maybe I'm wrong. If it does, why wasn't there blood anywhere else in the room besides where he died. I just didn't like it.
Other than that, it was a good, fun film.

One thing I like is the film is that it respects the audience intelligence. It gives us The Red Herrings in the form of subversions, so that the viewer will take it for granted. For example It seems like Ransom is set up as the JerkAss of the mostly nice family, so it seems the subversion is that Ransom is actually a nice guy after the rest of the families true nature is revealed. And of course there's the plot itself. It seems like the Subversion comes when were told what the answer to the Mystery is in the first act.
And then the 3rd act comes around and Subverts the Subversions

snippet.textDisplay:
How is it even POSSIBLE on this EARTH that you have never done a "wins" video for GATTACA? Remember the original idea for the channel? Movies which were underrated or underperformed, but had much more to them than they were given credit for? Well, THERE IT SITS, the prototypical movie for this channel, unwinned! I mean, whether it's Michael Nyman's score or the thematic parallels between this story and writer/director Andrew Niccol's sophomore effort, the lauded Truman Show (hint: Truman and Vincent are the same character, with the difference being that Vincent knows that he's in a cage not of his own making, and Truman does not. They even have their climactic moment in the waters!) or the fact that the movie has more always-a-win actors than you can shake a stick at (including, but not limited to Tony Shaloub, Blair Underwood, Xander Berkeley, the living treasure which is Una Damon, Maya Rudolph, Alan Arkin, and Ernest-frakkin'-Borgnine), or whether it's the use of color or symbolism - did I mention Michael Nyman's score-? or parallelism, or the fact that this movie called it on select-a-trait babies before it was a thing in the real world . . . Gattaca has all that you could want in a win video, and the ONLY reason everybody doesn't know about it is that it was completely mismarketed as an action thriller.

Seriously. You really need to consider doing this movie. It's a . . . well, it's a shame, at least, that you haven't done it long before now.

I mean, whether it's Michael Nyman's score or the thematic parallels between this story and writer/director Andrew Niccol's sophomore effort, the lauded Truman Show (hint: Truman and Vincent are the _same character,_ with the difference being that Vincent knows that he's in a cage not of his own making, and Truman does not. snippet.textDisplay: I gotta say, I think one of my favourite things among a plethora of favourite things about this movie is how Ransom is kind of introduced.
